@Mark Cousins

I saw a couple mentions of it in the comments, from solvers who struggled with it, but not much discussion. 

The word was vaguely familiar to me, or at least enough that I got it from the clue and the crosses.

@Tom S. 
In Greek, “PS” is written with one character: psi. 
More nit-pickily, Sam writes “written in English”, when a more correct description is “ written in Latin alphabet.”

@suejean 

It was too difficult, and the nonsensical palindromes did nothing for me, but truthful comments expressing dislike for a puzzle aren't really a thing here - they rarely get positive feedback, even when they are well argued and polite. I would post critical comments much more often if it were not for the (cultured but still personally unpleasant) animosity they are sometimes met with. 

There is also the fact that anything we post here has little effect on the editors - they do their own thing, and mostly quite well. A few disgruntled posters will change nothing, especially when they are outside the target group of these puzzles - foreigners, say.

@Rich in Atlanta 

That Inca clue was clearly from a cryptic puzzle, where the clue hints at the various parts of the answer (INCA HOOTS for Native Peruvian jeers) and then the normal reading of the phrase (IN CAHOOTS) for the conspiracy. The “parts of” tells you to look at parts of the phrase. 

But you knew that; this comment was for everyone else.

